🧠 1️⃣ Middleware kya hota hai?

Middleware ek function hota hai jo request aur response ke beech me execute hota hai.

👉 Simple flow:

Request → Middleware → Route Handler → Response

👉 Matlab:

Request aayi
Middleware ne check/modify kiya
Phir next step pe gaya
⚙️ 2️⃣ Middleware ka Structure
(req, res, next) => { }
req → request data
res → response bhejne ke liye
next() → next middleware/route ko call karta hai
💻 3️⃣ Basic Example
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// Middleware
app.use((req, res, next) => {
    console.log("Request received");
    next();
});

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
    res.send("Home Page");
});

app.listen(3000);
🔍 Flow
Request → Middleware (console log) → Route → Response

👉 Output:

Request received
🧩 4️⃣ Types of Middleware (Important 🔥)
🔹 1. Application-Level Middleware

👉 Pure app ke liye

app.use((req, res, next) => {
    console.log("App level middleware");
    next();
});
🔹 2. Route-Level Middleware

👉 Specific route ke liye

const checkAuth = (req, res, next) => {
    console.log("Auth checked");
    next();
};

app.get('/dashboard', checkAuth, (req, res) => {
    res.send("Dashboard");
});
🔹 3. Built-in Middleware

👉 Express ke andar already hota hai

app.use(express.json());

👉 JSON body ko parse karta hai

🔹 4. Third-party Middleware

👉 External packages

Example:

body-parser
cors
🔹 5. Error-handling Middleware

👉 Errors handle karta hai

app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
    res.status(500).send("Something went wrong");
});
🚀 5️⃣ Real Example (Authentication Middleware)
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

const auth = (req, res, next) => {
    const token = "123";

    if (token === "123") {
        next();
    } else {
        res.send("Unauthorized");
    }
};

app.get('/profile', auth, (req, res) => {
    res.send("Welcome User");
});

app.listen(3000);
